I mean I was dragged
all over the place.

00:51:21.460 --> 00:51:25.190 position:56%
Agents liked me because I did their
investigations and I did their work.

00:51:25.190 --> 00:51:28.150
But I thought it was unfair

00:51:28.150 --> 00:51:33.690
and that's why the judge
found systemic discrimination

00:51:33.690 --> 00:51:38.230 position:56%
within the FBI because of the system
that they had in place and using it,

00:51:38.230 --> 00:51:42.480 position:56%
so I would have joined even if these
incidents hadn't happened to me.

00:51:42.480 --> 00:51:44.330
Any other questions?

00:51:44.330 --> 00:51:47.180
&gt;&gt; Ed Mireles: Just to
follow up on what Sam said,

00:51:47.180 --> 00:51:51.920
our promotion system is based
on your performance, OK?

00:51:51.920 --> 00:51:56.790
How many arrests have you
made in the year 2016?

00:51:56.790 --> 00:51:58.860
How many people have
you interviewed?

00:51:58.860 --> 00:52:01.230
How many people have you indicted?

00:52:01.230 --> 00:52:04.400
How many people have you,
you know, prosecuted?

00:52:04.400 --> 00:52:05.700
And so on and so forth.

00:52:05.700 --> 00:52:10.830
If you are TDY from your office,
from your cases, for 3 months

00:52:10.830 --> 00:52:14.310
and some cases 6 months, OK?

00:52:14.310 --> 00:52:17.820
That's 6 months of you
not working, you're stuck.

00:52:17.820 --> 00:52:23.260
So you have less stats, less
evidence to prove your worth,

00:52:23.260 --> 00:52:26.970
prove your contribution
to the cause.

00:52:26.970 --> 00:52:31.360
And the other guys, the guys
that Sam would have to help,

00:52:31.360 --> 00:52:33.190
they would get their
stats, you know.

00:52:33.190 --> 00:52:34.970
Sam would help them arrest people

00:52:34.970 --> 00:52:37.440
and indict people and
interview people.

00:52:37.440 --> 00:52:38.740
But he never got the credit.

00:52:38.740 --> 00:52:40.950
The other guy got the credit, OK?

00:52:40.950 --> 00:52:43.440
So it's like Sam's like
[phonetic], "Hey Sam,

00:52:43.440 --> 00:52:48.110
you only have 2 arrests this
year and Bill over there has 22."

00:52:48.110 --> 00:52:50.970
It's like, "We're going
to promote Bill."

00:52:50.970 --> 00:52:55.070
It's like wait a minute, I helped
Bill with those 22 arrests.

00:52:55.070 --> 00:52:59.320
So that's how it affected
the individuals.

00:52:59.320 --> 00:53:00.850
&gt;&gt; Samuel Martinez:
What Ed's talking

00:53:00.850 --> 00:53:05.330
about is your statistical
accomplishments.

00:53:05.330 --> 00:53:10.460
But then I spoke last week it's
also your administrative profile.

00:53:10.460 --> 00:53:13.570
And your administrative profile
is sometimes more important

00:53:13.570 --> 00:53:15.290
than your statistics.

00:53:15.290 --> 00:53:18.080
If you look at some of
the way promotions happen

00:53:18.080 --> 00:53:21.760
within an agency it's who you
know and not what you know

00:53:21.760 --> 00:53:24.440
and so sometimes that happens.

00:53:24.440 --> 00:53:25.740
You have a question?

00:53:25.740 --> 00:53:27.040
&gt;&gt; Just a quick follow-up.

00:53:27.040 --> 00:53:30.280
Was [phonetic] there a mechanism
now in place as a follow-up to kind

00:53:30.280 --> 00:53:35.090
of that discrepancy where
someone assists in helping you

00:53:35.090 --> 00:53:40.060
by providing translation
or arrests, etc.,

00:53:40.060 --> 00:53:41.360
like now they get credit as well?

00:53:41.360 --> 00:53:43.990
&gt;&gt; Samuel Martinez: Well now
they have Spanish speakers

00:53:43.990 --> 00:53:45.590
that aren't agents.

00:53:45.590 --> 00:53:51.690
A lot of them are doing
what they call the wires;

00:53:51.690 --> 00:53:54.290
interceding the conversations.

00:53:54.290 --> 00:53:55.650
They have them doing that.

00:53:55.650 --> 00:54:00.030
But as far as -I know that
they were making attempts

00:54:00.030 --> 00:54:01.330
to hire more Spanish speakers.

00:54:01.330 --> 00:54:06.050
One of the things I didn't mention
was that if you were Anglo and came

00:54:06.050 --> 00:54:09.830
in under the Spanish
program, there was a period

00:54:09.830 --> 00:54:13.010
where they allowed you to opt out.

00:54:13.010 --> 00:54:15.430
Well that policy never
said it's only for Anglos

00:54:15.430 --> 00:54:18.450
so some Hispanic read
it and said, "Hey,

00:54:18.450 --> 00:54:19.910
I want to get out of the program."

00:54:19.910 --> 00:54:22.220
I said, "No you can't
because you're Hispanic."

00:54:22.220 --> 00:54:26.900
So it was unfair in that system.

00:54:26.900 --> 00:54:32.690
But yes, I'm pretty sure that
there's still cases out there

00:54:32.690 --> 00:54:37.630 position:56%
where somebody needs a Spanish
speaker because he goes into an area

00:54:37.630 --> 00:54:42.550
where a case agent
may not speak Spanish.

00:54:42.550 --> 00:54:52.790
I'm not sure how they're
accredited now, but the burden

00:54:52.790 --> 00:54:55.030
on Hispanics has diminished.

00:54:55.030 --> 00:54:58.930
I spoke to an agent last week
who came out to the presentation

00:54:58.930 --> 00:55:05.700
and he said it's a lot
better than what it was.

00:55:05.700 --> 00:55:07.110
Yes, madam?

00:55:07.110 --> 00:55:10.960
&gt;&gt; Do you have any advice for
young Hispanics entering the FBI

00:55:10.960 --> 00:55:13.470 position:56%
or other organizations like the FBI?

00:55:13.470 --> 00:55:17.430
Is it really just networking or
are there other things [inaudible]?

00:55:17.430 --> 00:55:19.170
&gt;&gt; Samuel Martinez:
Do I have any advice

00:55:19.170 --> 00:55:21.890
for people coming into the FBI?

00:55:21.890 --> 00:55:23.580
Yes. It's a great organization.

00:55:23.580 --> 00:55:27.510
There's a lot of excitement.

00:55:27.510 --> 00:55:30.510
Each day is different.

00:55:30.510 --> 00:55:35.500
You work with good people.

00:55:35.500 --> 00:55:37.980
[ Laughter ]

00:55:37.980 --> 00:55:40.780
Mostly good people -until they get

00:55:40.780 --> 00:55:47.390
into management then
they become evil.

00:55:47.390 --> 00:55:52.200
But no, I have great friends and
great colleagues in the bureau.

00:55:52.200 --> 00:55:55.730
It's a great career and I
recommend that field of work.

00:55:55.730 --> 00:55:59.410
They've now gone from the
criminal side more to security side

00:55:59.410 --> 00:56:02.860
because of the terrorism
threats in this country.

00:56:02.860 --> 00:56:08.160
But it's an exciting field and
it's a great opportunity for women

00:56:08.160 --> 00:56:10.950
and women are promoted
and they're in charge

00:56:10.950 --> 00:56:13.340
of offices and everything else.

00:56:13.340 --> 00:56:14.640
So it's a good opportunity.

00:56:14.640 --> 00:56:18.070
I have some books that are
signed back there to sell.

00:56:18.070 --> 00:56:25.190 position:56%
It's also on audible.com, but if
you live in D.C. it's under 10 hours

00:56:25.190 --> 00:56:27.510
so in 2 commutes you
can go through the book.

00:56:27.510 --> 00:56:31.110
[ Laughter ]

00:56:31.110 --> 00:56:34.470
But thank you very much for
having me and having Ed up here.

00:56:34.470 --> 00:56:36.270
We appreciate it.

